Here's a great one: the **View Transitions API**. It lets you create smooth, animated transitions between page states (or even across page navigations) with very little code—something that used to require heavy JavaScript libraries.

It's a nice talk topic because it's visually impressive, easy to demo, and solves a real pain point.

### Quick example

The core idea: wrap your DOM update in `document.startViewTransition()`, and the browser automatically animates between the old and new states.

```js
function updateContent() {
  // Fallback if the API isn't supported
  if (!document.startViewTransition) {
    swapTheContent();
    return;
  }

  // Browser snapshots before/after and animates the difference
  document.startViewTransition(() => {
    swapTheContent();
  });
}

function swapTheContent() {
  document.querySelector('h1').textContent = 'New Title';
  document.querySelector('.card').classList.toggle('expanded');
}
```

You can customize the animation with CSS:

```css
::view-transition-old(root),
::view-transition-new(root) {
  animation-duration: 0.4s;
}
```

And to make specific elements morph between states, give them a shared `view-transition-name`:

```css
.hero-image {
  view-transition-name: hero;
}
```

