Good topic for a short talk: the **View Transitions API**. It's a relatively recent web platform feature that lets you animate between DOM states (or even full page navigations) with very little code, instead of wiring up complex CSS/JS animation choreography.

Here's a quick example of the simplest case—animating a same-document DOM update:

```js
function updateView() {
  // Fallback if the browser doesn't support it
  if (!document.startViewTransition) {
    applyDOMChange();
    return;
  }

  document.startViewTransition(() => {
    applyDOMChange();
  });
}

function applyDOMChange() {
  document.querySelector('#content').textContent = 'New state!';
}
```

The browser snapshots the old and new states and cross-fades between them automatically. You can customize the animation with CSS:

```css
::view-transition-old(root),
::view-transition-new(root) {
  animation-duration: 0.3s;
}
```

And for shared elements that move between states, you give them a `view-transition-name` so the browser tweens them smoothly:

```css
.hero-image {
  view-transition-name: hero;
}
```

