CSS anchor positioning is a great pick—it solves a problem people have hacked around with JavaScript for years: tethering one element to another (tooltips, popovers, dropdowns) without manual position calculations or libraries like Popper.js.

Here's a quick example:

```html
<button class="anchor">Hover me</button>
<div class="tooltip">I'm anchored!</div>
```

```css
.anchor {
  anchor-name: --my-button;
}

.tooltip {
  position: absolute;
  position-anchor: --my-button;

  /* Position below the anchor, aligned to its left edge */
  top: anchor(bottom);
  left: anchor(left);
}
```

A couple of points that make for good talking material:

- **`anchor-name`** turns an element into a reference target, and **`position-anchor`** links the positioned element to it.
- The **`anchor()`** function lets you reference specific edges (`top`, `bottom`, `left`, `right`, `center`) of the anchor.
- **`position-try-fallbacks`** is the killer feature—it lets the browser automatically flip or shift the element when it would overflow the viewport, which is exactly the painful part you used to need JS for.

A quick fallback demo to show off:

```css
.tooltip {
  position-try-fallbacks: flip-block, flip-inline;
}
```

One caveat worth mentioning in the talk: browser support is still rolling out (Chrome/Edge have it; Firefox and Safari are behind), so pair it with a progressive-enhancement note.

