A great feature to cover is **CSS Anchor Positioning** — it’s a modern CSS capability that lets you position one element relative to another without manually calculating offsets in JavaScript.

It’s especially useful for things like:

- tooltips
- popovers
- dropdown menus
- context menus
- callouts

### Example: tooltip anchored to a button

```html
<button class="help-button">Help</button>

<div class="tooltip">
  This explains what the button does.
</div>
```

```css
.help-button {
  anchor-name: --help-button;
}

.tooltip {
  position: absolute;
  position-anchor: --help-button;

  top: anchor(bottom);
  left: anchor(center);

  transform: translateX(-50%);
  margin-top: 8px;

  background: black;
  color: white;
  padding: 0.5rem 0.75rem;
  border-radius: 0.4rem;
  font-size: 0.875rem;
}
```

The key idea is that the button defines an anchor:

```css
anchor-name: --help-button;
```

Then the tooltip positions itself relative to that anchor:

```css
position-anchor: --help-button;
top: anchor(bottom);
left: anchor(center);
```

So instead of writing JavaScript to measure the button and place the tooltip, CSS can handle the relationship directly.

