Here is a quick example of how to animate adding an item to a list:

**HTML:**
```html
<button id="add-btn">Add Item</button>
<ul id="list"></ul>
```

**JavaScript:**
```javascript
const btn = document.getElementById('add-btn');
const list = document.getElementById('list');

btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
  // 1. Wrap your DOM update in the API
  document.startViewTransition(() => {
    const newItem = document.createElement('li');
    newItem.textContent = `Item ${list.children.length + 1}`;
    list.appendChild(newItem);
  });
});
```

That's it. By wrapping the DOM manipulation in `document.startViewTransition()`, the browser automatically takes a snapshot of the old state and crossfades it into the new state. If you want to get fancy later, you can use CSS to customize exactly how specific elements animate in and out!

