Quick example:

```css
/* Style a card differently if it contains an image */
.card:has(img) {
  padding: 0;
}

/* A form field's label turns red when its input is invalid */
.field:has(input:invalid) label {
  color: crimson;
}

/* Dim all list items when any one is hovered, then highlight the hovered one */
ul:has(li:hover) li {
  opacity: 0.5;
}
ul li:hover {
  opacity: 1;
}
```

That last one is a nice live demo—it shows `:has()` reacting to state, not just structure.

