For years, web developers relied on a JSON hack—`JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj))`—to deep-clone objects. It was a clever workaround, but it was slow and completely broke if your object contained Dates, Sets, Maps, or circular references. 

`structuredClone()` is the modern, native web platform feature that finally solves this. It makes for a great short talk because everyone knows the old pain point, and the new solution is incredibly clean.

**Quick Example:**

```javascript
