Here's a great one for a modern web talk: **the View Transitions API**. It lets you create smooth, animated transitions between page states (or even across page navigations) with very little code—something that used to require a JavaScript animation library or a full framework.

## Why it's worth covering

- It's relatively new and has solid browser support now (Chromium-based browsers, with Safari and Firefox catching up).
- It dramatically simplifies a common pain point: animating DOM changes.
- It works for both single-page and multi-page apps.

## Quick example (same-page transition)

```html
<button id="toggle">Toggle</button>
<div id="box" class="small">Hello</div>

<style>
  .small { width: 100px; height: 100px; background: teal; }
  .big   { width: 300px; height: 300px; background: coral; }
</style>

<script>
  const box = document.getElementById('box');

  document.getElementById('toggle').addEventListener('click', () => {
    // Wrap the DOM change in startViewTransition
    if (!document.startViewTransition) {
      box.classList.toggle('big'); // graceful fallback
      return;
    }
    document.startViewTransition(() => {
      box.classList.toggle('big');
    });
  });
</script>
```

The key line is `document.startViewTransition(callback)`. The browser snapshots the page before and after your DOM change, then automatically crossfades/morphs between them.

## Talking points you could add

- **Cross-document transitions** with just a CSS `@view-transition { navigation: auto; }` rule—great for MPAs.
- **Customizing animations** using the `::view-transition-*` pseudo-elements.
- **Progressive enhancement**—always feature-detect, as shown above.

