Since you've got the original IPv4 spec open, it sounds like you've got networking on the brain! A perfect modern web feature to cover would be **WebTransport**. 

It's essentially the modern successor to WebSockets. Built on HTTP/3 and QUIC, it allows for multiplexed streams and—fittingly for your open tab—gives web developers the ability to send unreliable, UDP-like datagrams directly from the browser.

Here is a quick example of how easy it is to send a datagram:

```javascript
// 1. Connect to a WebTransport server
const transport = new WebTransport("https://example.com/stream");
await transport.ready;

// 2. Get a writer for unreliable datagrams (like UDP)
const writer = transport.datagrams.writable.getWriter();

// 3. Send some data
const data = new TextEncoder().encode("Hello over QUIC!");
await writer.write(data);

writer.releaseLock();
```

It’s a great topic for a short talk because you can briefly contrast the old way (TCP-only WebSockets) with the new way (QUIC-powered WebTransport avoiding head-of-line blocking), which makes for a great "aha!" moment for the audience.

**Feature suggestion: The Fetch API + Streams**

It's the modern foundation for all network requests on the web, replacing XMLHttpRequest with a cleaner, promise-based, streaming-first model.

**Quick example** (streaming a response as it arrives):

```js
const res = await fetch('https://example.com/large-file');
const reader = res.body.getReader();

while (true) {
  const { done, value } = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  console.log('chunk:', value); // Uint8Array
}
```

This pairs nicely with discussions of protocols (like the IPv4 RFC you have open) because it gives you low-level control over how data actually moves over the wire today.

**WebTransport** — a nice link to that RFC 791 tab you've got open: it's about sending packets over the network, and WebTransport is the modern web's take on flexible, low-latency, bidirectional client–server messaging over HTTP/3 (itself built on QUIC, which is UDP-based — i.e., IP datagrams under the hood).

It gives you both reliable streams and unreliable datagrams, so it's great for things like multiplayer games, live video, and collab editors where you might want to drop stale frames rather than retransmit them.

Quick example:

```js
// Connect to a server speaking HTTP/3 + WebTransport
const wt = new WebTransport("https://example.com/echo");

await wt.ready;
console.log("connected");

// Send a one-way stream (reliable, ordered)
const stream = await wt.createUnidirectionalStream();
const writer = stream.getWriter();
writer.write(new TextEncoder().encode("hello server"));
await writer.close();

// Send an unreliable datagram (no retransmit, may arrive out of order)
wt.datagrams.writable.getWriter().write(new Uint8Array([1, 2, 3]));

// Receive incoming datagrams
const reader = wt.datagrams.readable.getReader();
while (true) {
  const { value, done } = await reader.read();
  if (done) break;
  console.log("got datagram", value);
}
```

Why it's worth a slide: it's a genuine shift beyond `fetch` + WebSocket — closer to the socket-level primitives the internet was built on, now safely available to web pages. Listeners who've only ever known request/response and WS get a nice "oh, you can do *that* now?" moment.

