I highly recommend covering **Trusted Types**. 

It's a modern browser API designed to completely eliminate DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)—which is a massive source of CVEs. Instead of relying on developers to remember to sanitize inputs, Trusted Types allows you to configure the browser to outright reject raw strings when assigned to dangerous sinks like `innerHTML`.

Here is a quick example of how it works:

```javascript
// With Trusted Types enforced via Content Security Policy, 
// the browser blocks this dangerous assignment and throws an error:
// el.innerHTML = "<img src=x onerror=alert('XSS')>"; 

// Instead, you are forced to pass the data through a defined policy:
const sanitizerPolicy = trustedTypes.createPolicy('default', {
  createHTML: (input) => {
    // You'd typically use a real sanitizer library here like DOMPurify
    return input.replace(/</g, '&lt;').replace(/>/g, '&gt;'); 
  }
});

// Now, you create a "TrustedHTML" object...
const safeHtml = sanitizerPolicy.createHTML("<img src=x onerror=alert('XSS')>");

// ...and the browser allows the assignment!
document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = safeHtml; 
```

**Why it's great for a talk:** It shows a shift in web security from "hopefully we catch bad code in review" to "the browser literally won't compile/run the bad code." It's a great "defense-in-depth" topic.

**Trusted Types** (a security-focused web platform API).

It forces you to explicitly mark strings as safe before they can be used in dangerous sinks like `innerHTML`, helping eliminate whole classes of DOM-based XSS that still show up in CVEs.

Quick example:

```js
if (window.trustedTypes && trustedTypes.createPolicy) {
  const policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy('default', {
    createHTML: (input) => DOMPurify.sanitize(input)
  });

  // Now this is safe; raw strings are rejected
  el.innerHTML = policy.createHTML(userInput);
}
```

**View Transitions API** — great for a talk because it's visual and just a few lines of code.

It lets you animate between DOM states (route changes, list reorders, theme toggles) without a framework, using a built-in browser snapshot mechanism.

```html
<button id="toggle">Switch</button>
<div class="card">Hello</div>

<script>
  toggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
    document.startViewTransition(() => {
      document.querySelector('.card').classList.toggle('moved');
    });
  });
</script>

<style>
  .card { transition: transform .4s; }
  .moved { transform: translateX(200px); }
</style>
```

The key bit: `document.startViewTransition(callback)` snapshots the page, runs your DOM mutation, then crossfades old→new automatically. Any CSS transitions on the changed elements play during the crossfade. No libraries, no canvas, works today in Chromium and WebKit.

Good talk angle: "the platform absorbed another thing we used to need React/Framer Motion for."

