A good short-talk topic: **CSS feature queries for progressive enhancement**, especially `@supports selector()` and the emerging idea of named feature checks like `named-feature()`.

It’s practical because it shows how modern CSS can opt into newer platform features without breaking older browsers.

Quick example using a widely supported pattern:

```css
.card {
  padding: 1rem;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}

/* Use :has() only if the browser supports it */
@supports selector(.card:has(img)) {
  .card:has(img) {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 120px 1fr;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
}
```

Then you can mention the newer/future-facing direction:

```css
/* Conceptually: detect a named platform feature directly */
@supports named-feature(some-modern-feature) {
  /* enhanced styles here */
}
```

Talk angle: **“The web platform is moving from browser sniffing to capability sniffing.”**  
Instead of asking “Is this Chrome/Safari/Firefox?”, we ask “Does this feature exist?” and layer enhancements accordingly.

**Suggestion:** named-feature() in @supports

**Quick example:**
```css
@supports (named-feature: view-transitions) {
  .page {
    view-transition-name: main;
  }
}
```
This lets you safely use (or polyfill) newer named capabilities without breaking older browsers.

Happy to help brainstorm! Quick heads-up though: `named-feature()` isn't actually a real `@supports` feature as far as I know — you might be thinking of `selector()`, which *is* real and genuinely talk-worthy.

**`@supports selector()`** lets you feature-detect not just property/value support, but specific selectors — which historically you couldn't do. Great for safely adopting things like `:has()`.

```css
@supports selector(:has(*)) {
  /* Only apply :has() styles where supported */
  .card:has(img) {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;
  }
}

@supports not selector(:has(*)) {
  /* Fallback, e.g. add a class from JS instead */
  .card--has-image {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr;
  }
}
```

A few reasons it makes a good short talk topic:

- **Concrete win**: bridges the gap between "I want to use `:has()`" and "but browser support is uneven."
- **Broadens the mental model**: people usually think of `@supports` as just property/value checks — showing `selector()` (plus `font-tech()`, `font-format()`) expands what they think feature detection can do.
- **Pairs well with progressive enhancement narrative** — feels modern and intentional rather than hacky.

Other `@supports` companions worth a mention if you have room: `font-tech()` for variable/Color font detection, and the plain `@supports` + custom property combo for testing `@property` registration.

